posts.name: Phil Szymanowski
posts.cooked: The technical binder is impressive, but the 166-page drawing package is outstanding. It includes detailed assembly instructions such as aligning timing pulleys accurately, specifying materials and finishes, guidance on modifying COTS components, positioning sponsor logos on panels, post-processing steps, and information about every COTS supplier along with their part numbers. This level of detail in manufacturing drawings is unprecedented, especially given my extensive professional experience. I must admit, I‚Äôve never encountered such thorough assembly details in any manufacturing drawings throughout my career. If you missed out on this comprehensive drawing package, reconsider giving it another review. It‚Äôs a remarkable showcase of what mechanical drawings can achieve.

Question regarding the reduction of system backlash through broaching‚Äîwhether this is due to the COTS part not being available or because your broaching holds tighter tolerances than most vendors provide. If the latter, which broach are you using?

Additionally, could this relate to your sprockets and hubs having wider sizes to accommodate more surface area, similar to some hubs mentioned elsewhere? Would you still add shims in this scenario?

In general, it appears you have more custom-machined parts for torque transfer than initially anticipated. What kind of fabrication resources does 2056 have access to?

Could you link me to the quick exhausts mentioned earlier?

Thank you!

posts.name: Matt Golman

posts.name: Balraj Singh
posts.cooked: The team discusses methods to prevent gear backlash. Gearboxes have bonded all gears, including the motor pinion, using retaining compound to eliminate backlash. Discussions include using Loctite 609 to fill gaps in the bore. Questions arise about shim tape usage, broaching, and sprocket creation. Akash Rastogi mentions using a 15-year-old broach from McMaster-Carr, which is a push-fit on the shaft. Other engineers discuss setups involving arbour presses and careful alignment. Images of gear hubs and broaches are referenced. Zatack7 comments on the importance of a repeatable setup. Barrel adds info about timed-based vs command-based frameworks. Akash Rastogi asks about quick exhausts from Automation Direct.
